[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating source set options**\n\nI'm wondering if we should eliminate a separate source set and just place the helper in src/test/java. This way, there's no need for an extra source set. If the Java system class loader can access the test classpath, then the tests would be available. It seems like using a top-level helper in the same package allows for easy reference. So, I think a separate source set isn’t necessary. But would the helper be considered a generated test class? I'm still thinking about it.\n\n**Identifying potential errors**\n\nI'm considering the error \"com_google_collections.google_collections.FinalizerHidingSystemClassLoader not found.\" It might be due to the dependency not being included in the test runtime. The system loader is created during JVM startup, which complicates things. I’m thinking about how the system class loader can affect all tests and potentially alter the Finalizer globally. Also, I wonder if the custom system loader, which inherits from ClassLoader, works properly with class loading, especially for library classes. It's a bit tricky!\n\n**Clarifying custom loader behavior**\n\nI'm exploring the relationship between the custom loader and its parent, which seems to be the app class loader. The constructor for the Java system class loader uses the default system class loader as its parent, the AppClassLoader, which raises a question. If the custom loader is set as the system loader but still delegates loadClass calls to its parent, that means the FinalizableReferenceQueue class will actually be loaded by the AppClassLoader and not my custom loader. That's an important distinction!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_032442406b9b196e0169f5548b8dd0819f8928feefbba21f2f\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9VSZFabQnj6ZjuysXstNuDiUmDgOWYC7HA3tHSE6NUw0KoFbf-HCXynf65N_sg8PQBLvxjAqmqbms_CJHpz3YH_qECkbFIIo_A